I have always carried a bit 
more off. I want gleaming floorboards, 
the river’s reflection. She wants a row 
of jars: oats, coriander, thick 
green oil; I want nothing to store. 
She wants Wellesley reunions. I want 
words like lasers. She wants pomanders, 
linens, baby quilts, scrapbooks. She wants 
pomanders, linens, baby quilts, 
scrapbooks. She wants birthdays, theaters, flags, 
peonies. I want words like lasers. 
She wants birthdays, theaters, flags, peonies. 
I want words like lasers. She wants shrimp 
and sweat and salt; she wants chocolate. 
I want gleaming floorboards, the river’s 
